THE STATE OF SOUTH CAROLINA
In The Supreme Court
In the Matter of Harry 
Clayton DePew, Respondent.

Opinion No. 26440
Submitted January 28, 2008 - Filed February 25, 2008Â  

DEFINITE SUSPENSION


	
		
			
				Lesley M.
  Coggiola, Disciplinary Counsel, and Ericka M. Williams, Assistant Disciplinary
  Counsel, both of Columbia, forÂ  Office of Disciplinary Counsel. 
				John P.
  Freeman, of Columbia, for respondent.Â  
			
		
	


PER CURIAM:Â Â  In this attorney disciplinary
  matter, respondent and the Office of Disciplinary Counsel (ODC) have entered
  into an Agreement for Discipline by Consent pursuant to Rule 21, RLDE, Rule
  413, SCACR.Â  In the agreement, respondent admits misconduct and consents to the
  imposition of an admonition, public reprimand, or definite suspension not to
  exceed nine (9) months.Â  We accept the agreement and definitely suspend
  respondent from the practice of law in this State for nine (9) months.Â  The
  facts, as set forth in the agreement, are as follows.Â   
FACTS
On
  January 14, 2002, respondent applied for and obtained a driverâ€™s license from
  the Department of Motor Vehicles using the name and other identifying
  information of his deceased father but bearing his own photograph.Â  A report
  generated by the Department of Motor Vehicles Document Review and Fraud
  Detection Unit revealed the fraudulent license when it determined that the
  credentials used to obtain the license were that of a deceased person.Â  The
  information was forwarded to the South Carolina Law Enforcement Division which
  charged respondent with Fraudulent Application for a License.Â  See S.C.
  Code Ann. Â§ 56-1-510(5) (2006).Â  On June 13, 2007, respondent entered a plea of
  nolo contendere in the Orangeburg County Summary Court.Â Â   
LAW
Respondent
  admits that by his misconduct he has violated the following provisions of the
  Rules of Professional Conduct, Rule 407, SCACR:Â  Rule 
8.4(b) (lawyer shall not commit a criminal act that
    reflects adversely on the lawyerâ€™s honesty, trustworthiness, or fitness as a lawyer
    in other respects) and Rule 8.4(d) (lawyer shall not engage in conduct
    involving dishonesty, fraud, deceit, or misrepresentation). Â In
  addition, respondent admits his misconduct constitutes a violation of Rule 7,
  RLDE, of Rule 413, SCACR, specifically Rule 7(a)(1) (lawyer shall not violate
  Rules of Professional Conduct or any other rules of this jurisdiction regarding
  professional conduct of lawyers) and Rule 7(a)(5) (lawyer shall not engage in
  conduct tending to pollute the administration of justice or to bring the courts
  or the legal profession into disrepute or conduct demonstrating an unfitness to
  practice law).Â  Â Â Â Â Â 
CONCLUSION
We accept the Agreement for Discipline
  by Consent and definitely suspend respondent from the practice of law for nine
  (9) months.Â  Within fifteen days of the date of this opinion, respondent shall
  file an affidavit with the Clerk of Court showing that he has complied with
  Rule 30, RLDE, Rule 413, SCACR.Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â   
DEFINITE SUSPENSION.Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â   
TOAL, C.J., MOORE, WALLER, PLEICONES
  and BEATTY, JJ., concur.





